Epoch:0 | TOPIC | Scientist1:This is a timely and challenging problem, especially as single-view 3D reconstruction moves toward real-world applications where object orientation is unpredictable. Current methods often struggle with pose variability because the latent representations they learn are entangled with viewpoint-dependent features—this leads to poor generalization when the test-time orientation differs from training data.

One promising direction is to design a framework that explicitly disentangles pose from shape in the latent space. We could leverage geometric priors—such as symmetry, reprojection consistency, or equivariant neural networks under rotation groups (e.g., SO(3)-equivariant CNNs or steerable CNNs)—to build intrinsic, pose-invariant descriptors. For instance, instead of encoding shape relative to the observed viewpoint, we could align the input to a canonical pose implicitly through a pose-estimation bottleneck or via self-supervised alignment using differentiable rendering.

Another angle is contrastive learning in the latent space: by applying random rotations to the same object and enforcing similarity in shape representation while allowing pose codes to vary, we can encourage invariance. This could be combined with a pose-aware decoder that re-applies the estimated orientation during reconstruction, effectively factorizing shape and pose.

A key innovation would be to achieve this without requiring multi-view supervision or 3D ground truth during training—relying instead on single-view images with implicit supervision through reconstruction loss via differentiable rendering. If we can achieve robust pose invariance in a fully unsupervised or self-supervised manner, it would significantly advance the scalability of 3D reconstruction models to open-world settings.

What do you think about combining SO(3)-equivariant feature extractors with a canonical-space VAE? This might allow us to map arbitrary views into a rotation-invariant latent shape code while factoring out the pose, enabling more consistent reconstructions across orientations.
