Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in single-view 3D reconstruction lies in disentangling shape and pose when only 2D supervision is available—a problem exacerbated by the fact that objects can appear drastically different under varying orientations. While Paper 1 addresses shape-pose ambiguity using a pose-independent GAN, it still relies on implicit assumptions about canonicalization through adversarial priors. Paper 2 introduces a powerful idea—representation cycling—by breaking down learning into intermediate, cycle-consistent transformations, enabling unsupervised learning across domains. However, its application to human shape assumes strong anatomical priors (e.g., body parts), which may not generalize well to arbitrary object categories. Meanwhile, Paper 3 highlights geometric fidelity issues in reconstructions, especially around high-curvature regions, proposing geodesic-aware embeddings to preserve surface integrity.

My intuition is that true pose invariance cannot be achieved merely by adversarial regularization or reprojection consistency—it requires *explicit canonicalization* of input views into a pose-normalized latent space, but without requiring ground-truth pose labels or multi-view data. To achieve this, I propose integrating **implicit canonical coordinate prediction** with **cycle-consistent rendering**, inspired by representation cycling, but adapted for general object categories. The key innovation is introducing an intermediate "canonical feature map" that serves as a pose-invariant proxy of the object’s intrinsic geometry. This map is learned via a cycle: from image → predicted canonical view → 3D shape → rendered novel views → comparison with original input. Crucially, we avoid direct pose regression by instead enforcing consistency between forward and backward cycles using both photometric and structural losses.

Unlike prior work, our method does not assume access to segmentation masks (as in Paper 2) nor relies solely on global adversarial priors (as in Paper 1). Instead, it learns an implicit canonical frame through self-supervised cycle consistency, while preserving fine geometric details via a geodesically enhanced latent space (inspired by Paper 3). This fusion enables robustness to orientation variation, accurate topology recovery, and improved generalization across categories—all without pose annotations or multi-view inputs.

