  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework for learning pose-invariant latent representations in single-view 3D reconstruction by combining implicit canonicalization with cycle-consistent rendering and geodesic-aware geometry encoding. The central idea is to introduce an intermediate canonical feature space that abstracts away object pose while preserving intrinsic shape structure. Given a single RGB image of an object in arbitrary orientation, our model first predicts a 'canonical feature map'—a hypothetical view of the object in a learned canonical pose (e.g., front-facing, upright). From this canonical representation, a 3D shape decoder generates a complete mesh or point cloud. This 3D shape is then rendered back into multiple synthetic views using a differentiable renderer. These rendered images are compared to the original input through a bidirectional cycle loss: one path ensures that rendering the reconstructed 3D shape produces images consistent with the input; the reverse path enforces that re-estimating the canonical map from any rendered view converges to the same canonical representation. This cycle enforces pose invariance implicitly, without requiring pose labels. To further enhance geometric fidelity—especially in high-curvature regions—we embed surface points into a higher-dimensional space augmented with learned geodesic distances between neighborhoods, following the spirit of Geodesic-HOF (Paper 3), but integrated within the latent space of the 3D decoder. This allows the network to better capture fine surface details and avoid 'short-circuiting' during reconstruction. We train the entire pipeline end-to-end using only unpaired 2D images from a category (e.g., cars, chairs), making it highly applicable to real-world datasets where 3D ground truth or pose annotations are unavailable. The resulting latent space becomes inherently pose-invariant due to the canonical bottleneck and cycle consistency, enabling more accurate and robust reconstructions across diverse viewpoints. This approach significantly advances the state-of-the-art by unifying three critical components: (1) implicit canonicalization via cycle consistency, (2) pose-invariant representation learning without explicit pose supervision, and (3) geometric enhancement through geodesic-aware latent spaces. Potential impact includes broader applicability in robotics, AR/VR, and autonomous systems where reliable 3D understanding from monocular inputs is essential.",
