  "Experiment": "Our experimental plan consists of four phases: (1) Pipeline Architecture: We implement three core modules: (a) Self-Supervised Part Segmentation Network (SPS-Net) using contrastive learning over superpixels to extract semantic parts without labels; (b) Geodesic Graph Network (GGN) that builds dynamic graphs from segmented regions with edge weights based on predicted geodesic distances and normal consistency; (c) Topology-Aware Cycle Autoencoder (TACA) that encodes the graph into a latent vector and decodes it into a continuous 3D implicit field. A differentiable renderer closes the loop. (2) Training Protocol: We train end-to-end using only unpaired 2D images from ShapeNet and real datasets like Pix3D. No 3D or pose annotations are used. Losses include: (i) Reprojection Loss (SSIM + LPIPS) between input and closest rendered view, (ii) Cycle Consistency Loss on topology-aligned latents across renderings, (iii) Topological Regularization Loss using spectral divergence of graph Laplacians and Wasserstein distance between persistence diagrams (from topological data analysis), and (iv) Geodesic Smoothness Loss encouraging locally consistent surface interpolation. (3) Evaluation: We measure performance using Chamfer Distance, F-Score, Normal Consistency, and a new Topological Fidelity Score (TFS) based on Betti number preservation. We also introduce a Pose Invariance Metric (PIM) measuring latent similarity under large rotations. Baselines include DISN, HoloGAN, and variants of the original team idea. (4) Ablation Studies: We evaluate ablations removing the GGN, topological loss, or segmentation module. Ideal outcomes include: (i) minimal degradation in reconstruction quality under extreme rotations, (ii) superior handling of symmetric objects (e.g., tables, vases), (iii) higher fidelity in curved regions compared to point-cloud-based methods, and (iv) stable latent trajectories under continuous rotation.",
